questions.question: In a triangle, the measures of two angles are 55° and 65°. What is the measure of the third angle?
questions.explanation: The sum of the interior angles in a triangle is 180°. Subtract the given angles: 180° - 55° - 65° = 60°.
questions.score_improvement_tip: Remember that the sum of angles in any triangle is always 180°; use this to find missing angles quickly.

questions.question: In the figure, line segment AB is horizontal, and line segment BC is vertical, intersecting at point B. What is the measure of angle ABC?
questions.explanation: A horizontal and vertical line intersect to form a 90° angle.

questions.question: Solve for <math><mi>x</mi></math>: <math><mn>4</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math>.
questions.explanation: Add 12 to both sides: <math><mn>4</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>20</mn></math>. Divide by 4: <math><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math>.
questions.score_improvement_tip: Isolate the variable by performing inverse operations step by step.

questions.question: A straight line has an angle of 180°. If one angle measures 75°, what is the measure of the adjacent angle in degrees?
questions.explanation: Adjacent angles on a straight line sum to 180°: 180° - 75° = 105°.
questions.score_improvement_tip: Adjacent angles on a straight line are supplementary, summing to 180°.

questions.question_chart_svg: <svg width='400' height='300' viewBox='0 0 400 300' xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'><rect width='400' height='300' fill='white' /><line x1='50' y1='150' x2='350' y2='150' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><line x1='50' y1='250' x2='350' y2='250' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><line x1='200' y1='50' x2='200' y2='300' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><text x='180' y='140' font-size='12'>p</text><text x='220' y='140' font-size='12'>q</text></svg>
questions.question_chart_description: Two parallel horizontal lines intersected by a vertical transversal, with angles p and q labeled on the top line.
questions.question: In the figure, two parallel lines are intersected by a transversal. If the measure of angle p is 110°, what is the measure of angle q?
questions.explanation: Angles p and q are corresponding angles, which are congruent when lines are parallel, so angle q is 110°.
questions.explanation_chart_svg: <svg width='400' height='300' viewBox='0 0 400 300' xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'><rect width='400' height='300' fill='white' /><line x1='50' y1='150' x2='350' y2='150' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><line x1='50' y1='250' x2='350' y2='250' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><line x1='200' y1='50' x2='200' y2='300' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><text x='180' y='140' font-size='12'>p=110°</text><text x='220' y='140' font-size='12'>q=110°</text></svg>
questions.explanation_chart_description: The figure with angles p and q both labeled as 110°.
questions.score_improvement_tip: Identify corresponding angles when parallel lines are cut by a transversal; they are equal.

questions.skill: Ratios, rates, proportional relationships, and units
questions.question: A recipe calls for 3 cups of flour for every 2 cups of sugar. If 9 cups of flour are used, how many cups of sugar are needed?
questions.explanation: The ratio is 3:2. Set up proportion: <math><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mi>s</mi></mfrac></math>. Solve: <math><mi>s</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></math>.
questions.score_improvement_tip: Use cross-multiplication to solve proportions in ratio problems.

questions.question_chart_svg: <svg width='400' height='300' viewBox='0 0 400 300' xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'><rect width='400' height='300' fill='white' /><polygon points='100,250 200,50 300,250' stroke='black' fill='none' stroke-width='2' /><text x='90' y='270' font-size='12'>A</text><text x='190' y='40' font-size='12'>B</text><text x='290' y='270' font-size='12'>C</text></svg>
questions.question_chart_description: Triangle ABC with base AC and vertex B.
questions.question: Triangle ABC is isosceles with AB = BC. If angle at A is 50°, what is the measure of angle at B?
questions.explanation: Base angles at A and C are equal, but since AB = BC, base is AC, angles at A and C are equal. Angle at A is 50°, so angle at C is 50°, angle at B is 180° - 50° - 50° = 80°.
questions.explanation_chart_svg: <svg width='400' height='300' viewBox='0 0 400 300' xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'><rect width='400' height='300' fill='white' /><polygon points='100,250 200,50 300,250' stroke='black' fill='none' stroke-width='2' /><text x='90' y='270' font-size='12'>A 50°</text><text x='190' y='40' font-size='12'>B 80°</text><text x='290' y='270' font-size='12'>C 50°</text></svg>
questions.explanation_chart_description: Triangle ABC with angles labeled: A 50°, B 80°, C 50°.
questions.score_improvement_tip: In isosceles triangles, base angles are equal; subtract their sum from 180° to find the vertex angle.

questions.question: The function <math><mi>f</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></math> can be expressed as <math><mi>f</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>)</mo></math>. What is the value of <math><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></math>?
questions.explanation: Factor: <math><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>)</mo></math>, so a + b = 4.
questions.score_improvement_tip: To factor quadratics, find two numbers that multiply to the constant term and add to the linear coefficient.

questions.question: In a right triangle, the opposite side to a 30° angle is 5 units. What is the length of the hypotenuse? (Enter as an integer or decimal.)
questions.explanation: In a 30-60-90 triangle, hypotenuse is twice the shorter leg: 2 × 5 = 10.
questions.score_improvement_tip: Memorize special right triangle ratios for 30-60-90: sides 1 : √3 : 2.

questions.question: A item's price is increased by 20%, then decreased by 20%. What is the net percentage change?
questions.explanation: Assume $100. Increase: $120. Decrease: $120 × 0.8 = $96. Net: -4%.
questions.score_improvement_tip: Successive percentage changes are not additive; calculate step by step.

questions.question_chart_svg: <svg width='400' height='300' viewBox='0 0 400 300' xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'><rect width='400' height='300' fill='white' /><line x1='50' y1='250' x2='350' y2='250' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><line x1='100' y1='150' x2='300' y2='150' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><line x1='200' y1='50' x2='200' y2='300' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><text x='180' y='240' font-size='12'>r=65°</text><text x='220' y='140' font-size='12'>s</text></svg>
questions.question_chart_description: Two parallel lines intersected by a transversal, with angle r=65° on the bottom and angle s on the top.
questions.question: In the figure, the lines are parallel, and angle r measures 65°. What is the measure of angle s?
questions.explanation: Angle r and the alternate interior angle are 65°, but s is supplementary to that: 180° - 65° = 115°.
questions.explanation_chart_svg: <svg width='400' height='300' viewBox='0 0 400 300' xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'><rect width='400' height='300' fill='white' /><line x1='50' y1='250' x2='350' y2='250' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><line x1='100' y1='150' x2='300' y2='150' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><line x1='200' y1='50' x2='200' y2='300' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><text x='180' y='240' font-size='12'>r=65°</text><text x='220' y='140' font-size='12'>s=115°</text></svg>
questions.explanation_chart_description: The figure with angles r=65° and s=115° labeled.
questions.score_improvement_tip: Distinguish between alternate interior angles (equal) and consecutive interior angles (supplementary) in parallel line problems.

questions.skill: Systems of 2 linear equations in 2 variables
questions.question: Solve the system: <math><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn></math>, <math><mn>4</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn></math>. What is the value of <math><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>y</mi></math>? (Enter as an integer.)
questions.explanation: Multiply first equation by 2: <math><mn>4</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>24</mn></math>. Subtract second: <math><mn>11</mn><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>17</mn></math>, <math><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>17</mn><mn>11</mn></mfrac></math>. But wait, correct solve: actually x=3, y=2, x+y=5.
questions.score_improvement_tip: Use elimination by making coefficients match for one variable.

questions.question_chart_svg: <svg width='400' height='300' viewBox='0 0 400 300' xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'><rect width='400' height='300' fill='white' /><polygon points='100,250 200,100 300,250' stroke='black' fill='none' stroke-width='2' /><line x1='200' y1='100' x2='200' y2='250' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><text x='90' y='270' font-size='12'>D=40°</text><text x='290' y='270' font-size='12'>E</text><text x='190' y='90' font-size='12'>F</text></svg>
questions.question_chart_description: Triangle DEF with a line from F to the base DE, angle at D is 40°.
questions.question: In triangle DEF, angle D is 40°, and the line from F bisects the base DE. If the triangle is isosceles with DF = EF, what is the measure of angle at F?
questions.explanation: Since isosceles, base angles at D and E equal, but D is 40°, so E 40°, F 100°. The bisector doesn't change that.
questions.explanation_chart_svg: <svg width='400' height='300' viewBox='0 0 400 300' xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'><rect width='400' height='300' fill='white' /><polygon points='100,250 200,100 300,250' stroke='black' fill='none' stroke-width='2' /><line x1='200' y1='100' x2='200' y2='250' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><text x='90' y='270' font-size='12'>D=40°</text><text x='290' y='270' font-size='12'>E=40°</text><text x='190' y='90' font-size='12'>F=100°</text></svg>
questions.score_improvement_tip: In isosceles triangles with additional lines, first identify base angles.

questions.question: Solve for x and y: <math><mi>x</mi><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn></math>, <math><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>64</mn></math>. What is <math><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi></math>?
questions.explanation: Divide equations: <math><mfrac><mi>x</mi><msup><mi>y</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>/</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>y</mi></math> = 16/64, simplify to <math><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>x</mi><mi>y</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math>, so xy=4? Wait, correct: actually x=4, y=2, xy=8.
questions.score_improvement_tip: For nonlinear systems, divide or substitute to simplify.

questions.question: A circle has equation <math><msup><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mo>(</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>25</mn></math>. What is the radius?
questions.explanation: Standard form <math><msup><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>h</mi><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mo>(</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>k</mi><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>, so r=5.
questions.score_improvement_tip: Recognize the standard equation of a circle to identify center and radius.

questions.skill: Inference from sample statistics and margin of error
questions.question: A survey of 100 people has a margin of error of ±4%. If 52% favor an issue, what is the lower bound of the confidence interval? (Enter as decimal.)
questions.explanation: Lower bound: 52% - 4% = 48%, or 0.48.
questions.score_improvement_tip: Margin of error defines the range around the sample statistic.

questions.question_chart_svg: <svg width='400' height='300' viewBox='0 0 400 300' xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'><rect width='400' height='300' fill='white' /><line x1='50' y1='250' x2='350' y2='250' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><line x1='100' y1='150' x2='300' y2='50' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><line x1='200' y1='250' x2='250' y2='100' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><text x='80' y='240' font-size='12'>u=35°</text><text x='280' y='40' font-size='12'>v</text></svg>
questions.question_chart_description: Complex figure with intersecting lines and angles u=35°, v to find.
questions.question: In the figure, angle u is 35°. What is the measure of angle v?
questions.explanation: Using vertical and supplementary angles, v = 180° - 35° = 145°.
questions.explanation_chart_svg: <svg width='400' height='300' viewBox='0 0 400 300' xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'><rect width='400' height='300' fill='white' /><line x1='50' y1='250' x2='350' y2='250' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><line x1='100' y1='150' x2='300' y2='50' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><line x1='200' y1='250' x2='250' y2='100' stroke='black' stroke-width='2' /><text x='80' y='240' font-size='12'>u=35°</text><text x='280' y='40' font-size='12'>v=145°</text></svg>
questions.explanation_chart_description: The figure with angles u=35° and v=145° labeled.
questions.score_improvement_tip: Break down complex figures by finding vertical and linear pairs.

questions.question: Which expression is equivalent to <math><mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>20</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>16</mn></math>?
questions.explanation: Factor numerator: (x-4)(x-5), denominator: (x-4)(x+4).
questions.score_improvement_tip: Factor numerators and denominators to simplify rational expressions.

questions.question: A cylinder has radius 3 cm and height 10 cm. What is its volume in cubic cm? (Use π=3.14, round to nearest integer.)
questions.score_improvement_tip: Recall volume formula for cylinder: πr²h.

questions.question_chart_svg: <svg width='400' height='300' viewBox='0 0 400 300' xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'><rect width='400' height='300' fill='white' /><polygon points='100,250 150,100 250,150 300,250' stroke='black' fill='none' stroke-width='2' /><text x='90' y='270' font-size='12'>W=50°</text><text x='290' y='270' font-size='12'>Z</text></svg>
questions.question_chart_description: Quadrilateral with angles W=50°, Z to find.
questions.question: In the quadrilateral, opposite angles sum to 180°, angle W is 50°. What is angle Z?
questions.explanation: If cyclic or supplementary, Z = 180° - 50° = 130°.
questions.explanation_chart_svg: <svg width='400' height='300' viewBox='0 0 400 300' xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'><rect width='400' height='300' fill='white' /><polygon points='100,250 150,100 250,150 300,250' stroke='black' fill='none' stroke-width='2' /><text x='90' y='270' font-size='12'>W=50°</text><text x='290' y='270' font-size='12'>Z=130°</text></svg>
questions.explanation_chart_description: Quadrilateral with angles W=50° and Z=130° labeled.
questions.score_improvement_tip: For certain quadrilaterals, opposite angles are supplementary.
